THIS IS NOT AN EDITORIAL
This is not an editorial. If you were expertise the son's analysis of, and pronouncements on, a critical issue facing the campus
today, I’m sorry.
There were quite a few things to write about this week. Grinhell was Visited by a “new politician" and a “radical packﬁst,"
the radio station is having a hard time getting on the air, and
North Campus men can‘t decide whether their biggest enemy is
the Dean of Men or themselves.
My chief cause of concern, and the reason that there is no
editorial this week, is the problem of effectively. Basic to any edt-
social policy must be an objective and effectively. My objective
is simple: I wish to see students have the greatest opportunity to
live and learn, dramatically and otherwise, during their {our
years at Grinnell. I am sure that this objective does not differ
greatly from the wishes of the faculty and administration, but the
specsﬁc methods to foster this opportunity will. ii I am to pursuant anyone that my method is better than theory, I must be Ob‘
creative. shooting, demonstration, and posing fun may be removable and sotisiying costumes, but they will not continue anyone
or anything.
One of the most dangerous operators of effectively is the edimrial floral, If you read "the 5&3 feels that. r . r” you will probably think about the problem a bit when I sit down to write an
editorial, and I’m thinking about my girlfriend a thousand miles
away, an hourly tomorrow, and when I have to do my next laundry, I don't feel too much like an editorial we. But if I write ”I
{tel that . . .” you are likely to think “goods for you, Ancona_" If
1 am going to forestry continue you ot anything, without beginning
you into beginning that I am speaking for a committee of leading
thinking, it must be done by me, not "us.”
Getting a clear understanding of any issue on campus is difficult, and is further complicated by fifteen credits of courses (a
subtle plug for academic credit for the editorials). Getting a grass
an a major campus issue is difficult for an administrator to do In
a year, much less is student —- whose main concern, unlike the
administrator, is not campus problems — for a weekly deadline.
The use of reason, which is basic to any argument, seems to
be missing quite often from discussions on campus. When I pointed
up what seemed to me to b? considerations in Edward Holtmans’
argument during his South Lounge speech Wednesday, he replied
that it was a paradox. I guess it you‘re “right” and you face a
contamination, you’re allowed to Call it a paradox. But how can
you determine typically if you are right before reaching the contamination? You can't. And it you can‘t discuss your position log<
italic, you can’t discuss it at all.
1 have barely scratched the surface oi the problems surround.
log editorial writing in a liberal arts college in a world or change,
but if roll see an editorial next week, do me, and yourself, a favor.
,Think less about “where [he 5&B stands” and more about why.
Barry Ancona
